    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 1.04,
      "end": 5.42,
      "text": "This is a LibraVox recording. All LibraVox recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 6.26,
      "end": 10.58,
      "text": "For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibraVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 14.06,
      "end": 18.18,
      "text": "The Frogs Complaint Against the Sun, Anasap's Fable",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 20.6,
      "end": 24.14,
      "text": "Once upon a time, the sun was about to take himself a wife.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 24.84,
      "end": 33.78,
      "text": "The Frogs and Terror all raised their voices to the skies, and Jupiter, disturbed by the noise, asked them what they were croaking about.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 35.36,
      "end": 42.84,
      "text": "They replied, the sun is bad enough, even while he is single, drying up our marshes with his heat as he does.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 43.46,
      "end": 47.62,
      "text": "But what will become of us if he marries and begets other sons?",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 50.84,
      "end": 60.6,
      "text": "This has been an audio recording of the Frogs Complaint Against the Sun from Anasap's Fables, read by Andy Fluke of 13pennies.net for LibraVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
